discourse is best analyzed through its emergence from the mythological imagination of early China, and that it was unified by a set of notions about the Dao that was shared by all of its participants. The author introduces certain categories from the Western religious and philosophical traditions in order to bring out the distinctive qualities constituting this discourse and to encourage its comparison with other religious and philosophical traditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCosmogony, Ancient. 0aTaoism. 0aTaoist philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Taoism. 7aRELIGION / Taoism (see also PHILOSOPHY / Taoist).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791483176423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791483176/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles